  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "The term \"6/6 vision\" is used to describe normal visual acuity, which means a person can see at 6 meters what a person with normal vision can see at 6 meters. This is often referred to as \"20/20 vision\" in countries that use the imperial system, where 20/20 means a person can see at 20 feet what a person with normal vision can see at 20 feet.\n\n\"Myopia,\" also known as nearsightedness, is a condition where a person can see close objects clearly but distant objects appear blurry. If someone has \"6/6 myopia,\" it would imply that their vision is normal (6/6) despite having myopia, which is contradictory because myopia typically causes reduced visual acuity, especially for distant objects.\n\nIn practice, myopia is measured in diopters (D), which indicate the degree of refractive error. For example, a person with -1.00 D myopia has a mild form of the condition, whereas a person with -6.00 D myopia has a more severe case. The visual acuity in myopia is usually worse than 6/6, with values like 6/12, 6/18, etc., depending on the degree of myopia.\n\nSo, \"6/6 myopia vision\" is not a standard term and may be a misnomer. If you have concerns about your vision or myopia, it's best to consult an eye care professional for an accurate assessment and appropriate correction.",
